YES, &quot;there is a way to join two Java `LinkedList`s in O(1)&quot;!
  
Using reflection and changing (or destroying) the original lists. This solution is very dependent of the Java version and may fail for other versions or implementations - tested with OpenJDK 8. It will eventually also fail if run using a `SecurityManager` and/or missing the corresponding rights.

This code joins the 2nd list into the first and returns the first list:

````java
import java.lang.reflect.Field;
import java.util.LinkedList;

public class LLMerge {

    private final Field size;
    private final Field first;
    private final Field last;
    private final Field next;
    private final Field prev;
    
    LLMerge() throws ReflectiveOperationException {
        size = LinkedList.class.getDeclaredField(&quot;size&quot;);
        size.setAccessible(true);
        first = LinkedList.class.getDeclaredField(&quot;first&quot;);
        first.setAccessible(true);
        last = LinkedList.class.getDeclaredField(&quot;last&quot;);
        last.setAccessible(true);
        next = first.getType().getDeclaredField(&quot;next&quot;);
        next.setAccessible(true);
        prev = first.getType().getDeclaredField(&quot;prev&quot;);
        prev.setAccessible(true);
    }
    
    public &lt;E&gt; LinkedList&lt;E&gt; merge(LinkedList&lt;E&gt; l1, LinkedList&lt;E&gt; l2) throws ReflectiveOperationException {
        int size1 = size.getInt(l1);
        Object first1 = first.get(l1);
        Object last1 = last.get(l1);

        int size2 = size.getInt(l2);
        Object first2 = first.get(l2);
        Object last2 = last.get(l2);

        next.set(last1, first2);
        prev.set(first2, last1);
        last.set(l1, last2);
        size.setInt(l1, size1+size2);

        return l1;
    }
}
````

This code is just a prototype, so please note:  

 1. The second list should not be used after being merged, or risk unexpected behavior since the same `Node`s will be shared between both lists. If that is a problem, code must be added to reset the fields of the second list, basically clearing it. 
  2. This code also does not handle empty lists correctly - missing `null` checks (`first` and `last` nodes)

